##Chapter 5: Embracing Cognitive Humility
In the earlier chapters, we questioned the deep-rooted belief in "infinity" and introduced Non-Infinity Theory — the possibility that the universe runs in finite cycles.

But this raises an important question: if the universe is finite, why do so many people feel so strongly that it must be infinite? Why do we so easily believe that things with no clear end must go on forever?

To answer this, we need to shift our focus away from the universe for a moment — and turn inward, to our senses and our mind. This is where the illusion of infinity really starts. Our senses and mind don't simply show us reality like a perfect mirror. They are more like complex filters and builders — taking limited data and creating a meaningful, connected world inside our heads.



5.1　Is Infinity the Truth of the Universe, or Just Our Projection?
People often say: "The universe is infinite," "Time is endless," "Math can go on forever." But what are those beliefs based on?

We have never truly seen infinity. All our knowledge comes from limited experiences — limited lifespans, limited senses, limited tools, and limited time to observe. We imagine and extend from the finite, and then we declare that infinity exists.

But what if "infinity" is not a fact of the universe, but a natural assumption our minds make when facing the unknown? When we can't see the end of something, we automatically assume it must go on. This may not be logic — it may be a kind of psychological defense, helping us avoid the fear of endings, emptiness, or uncertainty.

History shows us examples of this. Long ago, people looked up at the stars and believed the sky stretched on forever with no edge. But later we learned the universe is finite but expanding. The universe didn't change — our way of understanding it did.

Even in math, we use things like infinite decimals or infinite series — but only in a limited way. No one ever uses the full digits of π to build anything in the real world. This shows that even in math, infinity is a tool, not something we can ever fully realize.

In short: "infinity" might not be a feature of the universe. It might be a projection of our mind, created when we reach the edge of what we can know.



5.2　Our Senses Have Blind Spots — and Our Brain Fills the Gaps
Our understanding of the world starts with our senses — we see light, hear sound, feel touch. But these senses have clear limits.

Our vision is limited — we can only see visible light, from red to violet. Most of the light in the universe, like infrared, ultraviolet, X-rays, and radio waves, is completely invisible to us. Our hearing is narrow — humans only hear certain sound frequencies, while animals like bats and dogs can hear sounds we cannot detect at all. And our sense of time is imperfect — we don't experience time continuously. Fast-moving images appear smooth because of how our brain processes them, which is exactly how movies and animations work.

Despite these limits, our brain doesn't just give up. It has developed powerful systems for filling in the gaps and recognizing patterns. Even with broken or incomplete information, our brain guesses and completes the picture for us. Gestalt psychology shows how we naturally connect dots into lines, or fill in incomplete shapes to make them whole.

This ability to "auto-complete" reality is useful — it helps us understand the world quickly. But it also creates illusions. When we see repeated patterns without clear ends, like ocean waves or the changing seasons, we assume they are infinite. But maybe that's just our mind stretching limited information and mistaking repetition for infinity.



5.3　The Filter of the Mind and the Construction of Reality
Beyond the limits of our senses, our minds also act as powerful filters that constantly select, interpret, and build what we believe is "reality." Reality isn't something purely objective that exists outside of us — it is shaped through the interaction between the outer world and our inner mind.

Our beliefs and expectations shape what we see. We interpret information based on what we already think is true, what we've experienced before, and what we believe deep down. If someone strongly believes in "infinite cycles," they will easily find things in daily life that seem to support that idea, while ignoring signs that point the other way.

Our culture and language also shape our thinking. Many abstract ideas, including "infinity," are created through language — not through direct experience in the physical world. When we say "infinity," we are using a concept, not pointing to something we have actually seen or touched.

We also naturally want to give meaning to things, especially when we face uncertainty or things we cannot fully understand. When we can't see the edge of the universe or don't know when time ends, "infinity" becomes a convenient idea to help make sense of the unknown. It is a mental shortcut — a way to make things feel more stable and clear.

Our deep belief in "infinity" comes from these mental filters and constructions. We don't actually see or experience infinity — we imagine it. Our minds project the idea of "infinity" onto repeated patterns, even when those patterns are still limited. This connects back to the main point of this book: "infinity" is not something that truly exists in the world — it is something that lives in the way we think.



5.4　The Illusion of Probability: A Lesson from Playing Cards
Now let's look at something simpler and closer to everyday life: a deck of playing cards. This can help us see how humans give special meaning to things and create the feeling of "infinite" possibility.

Imagine you draw four cards one by one from a standard deck of 52 cards and get: Ace of Diamonds, Ace of Clubs, Ace of Hearts, Ace of Spades. Your friends might be shocked: "What are the odds?! This feels like a miracle!" But now imagine drawing: 2 of Diamonds, 4 of Clubs, 7 of Hearts, 9 of Spades. Most people wouldn't care. It seems like a completely ordinary hand.

Yet both combinations are equally unlikely. The math is exactly the same for both:
(1/52) × (1/51) × (1/50) × (1/49) = 1 in 6,497,400

The only difference is the meaning we gave the Ace. In most card games, the Ace is the highest card — it wins games, it represents luck and power. So drawing all four Aces feels like "super luck" or something almost impossible. The other cards carry no special meaning in our game rules, so we feel nothing at all.

This example shows how our idea of "probability" can be twisted by the meanings we attach to things. It is the same with our idea of "infinity." We often label something "infinite" just because it matches our deep hopes or beliefs — like "endless time" or "eternal love." But these are meanings we invented, not proven facts about the universe.

Rare does not mean impossible. Drawing four Aces is rare, but not magical. It just feels that way because we gave it special meaning. Likewise, when we see repeating patterns in nature — like seasons or ocean waves — we may call them "infinite." But that is because our minds are trained to find meaning, not because those patterns truly have no end.

If we could step back and drop all our human-made rules and emotional labels, we would realize that every specific state of the universe may have the same basic chance of happening, that "infinity" is not a feature of the universe but a label created by the human mind, and that the universe is likely a limited but ongoing cycle — there is no truly "infinite order" and no absolute “impossible."

Drawing four Aces is just one possible outcome among many. The only reason it seems special is because we decided it was. And that decision — that rule we invented — is the root of our misunderstanding of "infinity." If we can be fooled by a simple card game, how much more easily might we misjudge the vast universe?



5.5　True Philosophy: The Wisdom of "Not Knowing"
On our journey to find truth, humans often want a "final answer" — a concept that can explain everything. "Infinity" is one of those powerful words we reach for. We say the universe is infinite, time is infinite, math can go on forever — but are these ideas based on real experience? Or are they products of imagination, trying to deal with the unknown?

Aristotle once said: "The beginning of knowledge is the recognition of ignorance." We don't start thinking because we have all the answers — we begin by realizing how little we know. This willingness to face "not knowing" is the true starting point of philosophy.

Socrates went further: "The only thing I know is that I know nothing." This wasn't a joke — it was a deep understanding of how limited human knowledge really is. He saw that the biggest blind spot is often not realizing what we don't know.

True wisdom doesn't come from knowing everything. It comes from accepting that some questions might never be fully answered. Maybe "infinity" is just a label we put on things we can't understand — a way to avoid asking what comes next. But doing that doesn't solve the mystery. It only hides it. True philosophy isn't about rushing to fill the unknown with the word "infinity." It is about being humble enough to stay with the unknown, to think deeply, and to keep exploring.


Perceptual Humility: To See More, Let Go of Yourself
We often think that "knowing" means collecting more facts or becoming more logical. But real understanding often starts when we let go of our ego. Without humility, we cannot see a bigger truth.

Imagine an ant walking on the ground. It might only understand the world as a flat surface. It cannot imagine "above" or "inside." But that doesn't mean it isn't living in a three-dimensional world — it just can't sense it. Humans are the same. Our eyes only receive flat, two-dimensional images. Our sense of three-dimensional space is something our brain builds from clues like shadows and depth. We live in a 3D world, but we don't actually see it directly — our mind constructs it for us.

So when people ask whether we can see the fourth or fifth dimension, they often watch videos showing rotating shapes from higher dimensions. These help our imagination, but they are still just 3D models trying to describe something beyond them.

To truly understand the fourth dimension, it is not about looking harder. It is about removing the camera — letting go of being just an outside observer. You need to use your imagination and inner perception to understand something from all angles at once, including the inside. In other words, to see higher levels of reality, the first step is not to "see more clearly." It is to let go of the part of you that already thinks it sees everything.

The more we believe "what I see is the truth," the more we block ourselves from seeing deeper. You don't reach a higher reality because you are stronger — you reach it because you are more humble. When you stop putting yourself at the center, the universe begins to show you its deeper structure.

This is the spirit of Non-Infinity Theory: it doesn't claim to have all the answers. It simply reminds us that "infinity" may be just a mental shortcut we use to handle the unknown. What truly matters is not chasing an unprovable infinite. What matters is learning to live in this limited — but real — world, and finding meaning right here.



5.6　Freedom Within Limits
If the universe is limited, does that mean we are small, trapped, or powerless? Actually, it is the opposite.

In a limited world, we can understand what true freedom really means. In a fake "infinite" world, choices lose their weight. You might think "there is always more time" or "I can always try again." But in a real, limited world, every choice matters.

Life is short — and because it is short, it becomes precious. Because it doesn't repeat forever, we learn to value it, to choose carefully, and to fill every moment with meaning. Within limits, we are given the real power to create, define, and shape our lives.

Recognizing the limits of our senses and minds is not meant to make us feel weak. It gives us a more honest and deeper understanding of ourselves. It shows us that what we "see" is always filtered, and what we "understand" is always shaped by a particular framework.

Non-Infinity Theory doesn't try to shrink the universe. It helps us understand our place in it more clearly. When we realize our knowledge is limited, we become more open, more curious, and more humble. This humility frees us from chasing the illusion of "infinity." Instead, we find real meaning and real freedom within what is limited — but true.


Before we move on, take a moment to think: your instinct that the universe is "infinite" — does it come from real experience, or from your mind automatically filling in the blank when you couldn't see the edge? If it's the second one, are you still willing to keep believing it?
